text: A driver who caused the deaths of two young brothers returning home from the local swimming pool in regional New South Wales has been jailed by a judge who said cars were not playthings.As a mother and four boys walked along a footpath after visiting the pool in Wellington, a mother saw an out-of-control red Commodore heading straight for a mother and four boys.a mother tried to throw four boys out of the way but an out-of-control red Commodore the crash into a mother and four boys, killing a mother's two young sons aged six and seven.A driver who caused the deaths of two young brothers returning home from the local swimming pool in regional New South Wales, was jailed on Friday for 13 years with a non-parole period of nine years.A driver who caused the deaths of two young brothers returning home from the local swimming pool in regional New South Wales was speeding before performing fishtails along a residential street in Wellington and stopped when an out-of-control red Commodore hit a fence causing the bumper to be torn.But A driver who caused the deaths of two young brothers returning home from the local swimming pool in regional New South Wales resumed doing fishtails and an out-of-control red Commodore skidded out of control, hit a brick wall and continued along a footpath colliding with two young brothers.“The message must be sent to our community in clear and unequivocal terms that cars are not playthings,” a judge who said cars were not playthings said in the Dubbo district court.A driver who caused the deaths of two young brothers returning home from the local swimming pool in regional New South Wales pleaded guilty to the manslaughter of two young brothers, on 5 January 2021.He also pleaded guilty to aggravated dangerous driving occasioning grievous bodily harm to a mother and to a boy whose leg had to be amputated.A driver who caused the deaths of two young brothers returning home from the local swimming pool in regional New South Wales also admitted a charge of wanton driving occasioning bodily harm to the fourth young boy.

text: A driver who caused the deaths of two young brothers returning home from the local swimming pool in regional New South Wales has been jailed by a judge who said cars were not playthings.As a mother and four boys walked along a footpath after visiting the pool in Wellington, a mother saw an out-of-control red Commodore heading straight for a mother and four boys.a mother tried to throw four boys out of the way but an out-of-control red Commodore the crash into a mother and four boys, killing a mother's two young sons aged six and seven.A driver who caused the deaths of two young brothers returning home from the local swimming pool in regional New South Wales, was jailed on Friday for 13 years with a non-parole period of nine years.A driver who caused the deaths of two young brothers returning home from the local swimming pool in regional New South Wales was speeding before performing fishtails along a residential street in Wellington and stopped when an out-of-control red Commodore hit a fence causing the bumper to be torn.But A driver who caused the deaths of two young brothers returning home from the local swimming pool in regional New South Wales resumed doing fishtails and an out-of-control red Commodore skidded out of control, hit a brick wall and continued along a footpath colliding with two young brothers.“The message must be sent to our community in clear and unequivocal terms that cars are not playthings,” a judge who said cars were not playthings said in the Dubbo district court.A driver who caused the deaths of two young brothers returning home from the local swimming pool in regional New South Wales pleaded guilty to the manslaughter of two young brothers, on 5 January 2021.He also pleaded guilty to aggravated dangerous driving occasioning grievous bodily harm to a mother and to a boy whose leg had to be amputated.A driver who caused the deaths of two young brothers returning home from the local swimming pool in regional New South Wales also admitted a charge of wanton driving occasioning bodily harm to the fourth young boy.

text: Based on current trends, About 278 million people in Africa – approximately one-fifth of the total population – is projected to rise to 310 million by 2030.“Africa is the increase backwards in Africa's efforts to end hunger, food insecurity and malnutrition,” Abebe Haile-Gabriel, an the UN’s Food and Agricultural Organisation (FAO) assistant director general and the UN’s Food and Agricultural Organisation (FAO)'s regional representative for Africa, told a conference in Addis Ababa on Monday.Abebe Haile-Gabriel, an FAO assistant director general and its regional representative for Africa, attributed the increase to “multiple and overlapping shocks and protracted crises in Africa” including the climate crisis, the lingering effects of the Covid pandemic, regional conflicts and the global surge in fuel prices amid Russia’s invasion of Ukraine.Abebe Haile-Gabriel, an FAO assistant director general and its regional representative for Africa, said that most African countries lack the resilience and mechanisms to cope with these shocks, resulting in the livelihoods of millions of people being wiped out.‘There’s a path towards death that people travel’: how hunger destroys lives and communitiesRead more“This is not sustainable,” said Abebe Haile-Gabriel, an FAO assistant director general and its regional representative for Africa,.
